<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div style="background:#e6d9bd;padding:8rem 0 3rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8">
      <a href="/insights" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(25,24,23,0.6);text-decoration:none;margin-bottom:2rem;transition:color 0.2s;"
        onmouseover="this.style.color='#6b4610'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(25,24,23,0.6)'" onclick="if(history.length>1&&document.referrer.indexOf(location.origin)===0){history.back();return false}">
        &larr; Back
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#6b4610;margin-bottom:1rem;">Market Report · Spring 2026 · 9 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#191817;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Brisbane Inner East Market Report: Spring 2026
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(25,24,23,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        What sellers in Bulimba, Hawthorne, Morningside, Cannon Hill, Camp Hill, Coorparoo, Murarrie, Seven Hills, Norman Park, and Carina need to know before listing in September, October, or November 2026.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <div style="padding:1rem 1.25rem;background:rgba(107,70,16,0.06);border-left:3px solid rgba(107,70,16,0.3);margin:0.5rem 0;">
        <p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);margin:0;line-height:1.7;"><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">A note on data:</strong> Figures cited here are drawn from CoreLogic (Cotality), the Reserve Bank of Australia, the Australian Bureau of Statistics, and the REIQ. Where a number could not be verified to a credible institutional source, it has been omitted. For a specific assessment of your property's current value, speak with an agent active in your suburb.</p>
      </div>

      <p>Spring is historically Brisbane's most active selling window, the period when listing volumes lift, buyer numbers expand, and weekend open homes carry the strongest attendance of the calendar year. The market entering spring 2026 is in a different shape from spring 2025. Interest rates have moved up, not down. Stock remains tight in the most desirable inner east streets. Brisbane has continued to outperform the national average on capital growth, and migration from NSW into South East Queensland has stayed at decade-high levels.</p>

      <p>This report sets out what has changed since the Q2 2026 update, what the credible institutional data is currently showing, and what it means for owners in Bulimba, Hawthorne, Morningside, Cannon Hill, Camp Hill, Coorparoo, Murarrie, Seven Hills, Norman Park, and Carina who are weighing a spring sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Median values and growth, Brisbane and the inner east</h2>

      <p>The most current CoreLogic Home Value Index, published as the May 2026 release covering data to 30 April, recorded Brisbane's median dwelling value at $1,222,906, up 1.2 per cent for the month and 19.1 per cent over the year. Brisbane was named the strongest capital city performer in the April release. The March 2026 release had recorded a Brisbane median of $1,101,151, a 1.8 per cent monthly move and a 19.0 per cent annual increase, which gives some sense of the pace of growth through the first quarter.</p>

      <p>The REIQ Queensland Market Monitor for Q1 2026 recorded quarterly growth of 4.9 per cent for Brisbane houses and 6.1 per cent for Brisbane units. Median days on market for Brisbane houses sat at 21 days in January 2026, effectively unchanged from 22 days a year earlier, while units took around 54 days. These figures cover greater Brisbane and average across the spectrum from outer suburbs to the inner ring. The inner east, on the evidence of recent campaigns, has continued to transact at the faster end of that range for well-prepared family homes.</p>

      <p>Inner east suburb-level medians require time to settle as Q2 sales work through reporting, and a single quarter of suburb-level data carries more noise than the wider Brisbane index. Sellers should treat the headline Brisbane growth figure as context, not as a forecast for their specific street. The right reference point for any individual property is a current comparable sales analysis, drawn from sales of similar homes in similar pockets, settled in the past three to six months.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Buyer pool composition</h2>

      <p>The Brisbane buyer pool entering spring 2026 has three structural sources of depth.</p>

      <p>The first is interstate migration. ABS data on internal migration shows NSW lost a net 33,400 residents to other states in the year to September 2025, the largest annual outflow on record. Queensland captured the majority of that movement. The state recorded net interstate migration of 21,595 people in 2024 to 2025, with NSW contributing 24,328 of those people and more than 14,000 settling in South East Queensland. The Queensland Government Statistician's Office has noted Queensland accounts for around 25 per cent of national population growth while delivering under 20 per cent of dwelling completions, a structural mismatch that supports demand at the suburb level.</p>

      <p>The second source is owner-occupier demand from within the inner east. Families upgrading from a first home to a school-catchment property, downsizers moving from a large block to a low-maintenance home in the same suburb, and intra-east relocations from the north to the south of Wynnum Road or vice versa, all of these represent buyers whose decisions are driven less by interest rate movements and more by life-stage timing.</p>

      <p>The third is the first home buyer cohort, supported in 2026 by federal and state-level policy continuing to encourage first home buyer entry. This buyer is most active at the lower end of the inner east price range, including Cannon Hill, Murarrie, Seven Hills, and parts of Carina, where stock under $1.2 million still appears regularly.</p>

      <p>The investor pool remains a smaller share of buyer activity in the established inner east compared with the inner-fringe apartment markets. Owner-occupier demand is the dominant force on the demand side for freestanding houses in Bulimba, Hawthorne, Norman Park, Balmoral, and the upper end of Morningside.</p>

      <ResourceCTA slug="comparable-sales-worksheet" />

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Supply, days on market, and auction clearance</h2>

      <p>Stock levels remain the defining feature of the Brisbane inner east. Aggregated listings data covering the Brisbane property market through March and April 2026 showed total listings down 13.7 per cent year on year, while new listings rose 3.3 per cent year on year, indicating that new supply is being absorbed almost as quickly as it arrives. Spring will test that absorption rate as listing volumes rise into September and October, but the underlying gap between accumulated stock and active buyers heading into the season is a meaningful tailwind for vendors with well-prepared properties.</p>

      <p>On the building side, ABS Building Approvals data tells the same supply-side story. Queensland total dwelling approvals fell 6.4 per cent in March 2026, having moved erratically through January and February, with private sector house approvals rising 7.2 per cent in March on a more positive note. Approval volumes do not flow into completed stock for many months, and the inner east, where most growth is renovation rather than new construction, sees little direct relief from broader Queensland approvals.</p>

      <p>Brisbane auction clearance rates moved through a softer phase across April and early May 2026 in line with the May rate decision. Compiled weekly results showed clearances of 55.7 per cent for the week ending 3 April, 58.1 per cent for the week ending 12 April, and a peak of 60.9 per cent in mid April, before easing to 48.8 per cent in early May. The April monthly average compiled by industry watchers came in at 56.6 per cent. These results sit below the long-run 60 to 70 per cent band considered indicative of seller-favourable auction conditions, which means auction remains effective only when reserves are set carefully against current evidence and the property type genuinely suits the auction method.</p>

      <p>For days on market, REIQ data and aggregated portal data both place Brisbane around 18 to 21 days for houses through Q1 2026, with the most desirable inner east family homes commonly transacting faster when preparation, pricing, and presentation are aligned.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Interest rates and borrowing capacity</h2>

      <p>The RBA's monetary policy path through the first half of 2026 has been the most material change for Brisbane buyers compared with this time last year. The cash rate moved from 3.60 per cent at the end of 2025 to 3.85 per cent on 4 February 2026, then to 4.10 per cent on 18 March 2026, and to 4.35 per cent on 5 May 2026 by an eight-to-one majority on the Monetary Policy Board. The next decision is scheduled for 16 June 2026, with ASX 30 Day Interbank Cash Rate Futures pricing at the time of writing reflecting a low probability of a further increase to 4.60 per cent.</p>

      <p>The practical effect on Brisbane buyer borrowing capacity is significant. Each 25 basis point increase reduces maximum borrowing for a typical owner-occupier on a single income by roughly 2 to 3 per cent. The cumulative move from 3.60 per cent to 4.35 per cent over five months has meaningfully reduced the size of mortgage some buyers can carry, particularly those previously borrowing close to their assessment ceiling.</p>

      <p>The translation into the Brisbane inner east market has not been uniform. Properties priced above $1.5 million, where buyer equity levels are typically higher and the buyer pool less dependent on borrowing at the maximum, have shown comparatively more resilient demand. Properties at the lower end of the inner east, where buyers more often rely on near-maximum borrowing, are seeing more conditional offers, longer finance-condition periods, and greater scrutiny on price guides. This pattern is what a seller in Cannon Hill, Murarrie, or Seven Hills should expect from their campaign, and it is also a feature an experienced local agent will price into both the campaign strategy and the negotiation framework.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What this means for sellers in spring 2026</h2>

      <p>Spring 2026 is shaping up as a positive but discerning market for inner east vendors. The structural conditions remain in seller-friendly territory, low total stock, sustained interstate migration, strong wage growth in the local economy, and continued underlying demand from owner-occupiers who treat housing as a place to live rather than a discretionary purchase. The cyclical conditions, including higher cash rates and softer auction clearance, mean buyers are doing more diligence, taking longer on inspections, and being firmer on price guides that look stretched.</p>

      <p>The practical implications for a seller listing in September to November 2026 are clear enough. Preparation matters more than it did at the 2021 peak, because the buyer is no longer willing to overlook visible issues in the rush to secure a property. Pricing accuracy matters more than it did when stock was even tighter, because buyers in 2026 are well-researched and price guides that diverge meaningfully from comparables attract fewer offers, not higher ones. The choice of method (auction, expression of interest, private treaty) needs to reflect the property type, the buyer pool, and the realistic depth of competition for that specific home, not a default house-style preference.</p>

      <p>Sellers with timing flexibility may benefit from launching earlier in spring rather than later. The window from late September through October typically carries the highest volume of qualified buyers active in the market and the strongest attendance at open homes. Campaigns launching from late November onwards run into thinner pre-Christmas attention and a competing pool of vendors trying to settle before year end.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Suburbs to watch this spring</h2>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Bulimba.</strong> The most consistently demanded suburb in the inner east, with Oxford Street, the river, and the Bulimba State School catchment all anchoring buyer interest. Stock on the southern side of Oxford Street and along the river in particular has remained tight. <a href="/insights/selling-in-bulimba" style="color:#b98229;">Selling in Bulimba</a> covers what a campaign looks like in detail.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Hawthorne.</strong> Hawthorne has continued to trade strongly into 2026, particularly the streets between Riding Road and the river. The cinema and Hawthorne Park precincts both anchor lifestyle buyer interest. <a href="/insights/selling-in-hawthorne" style="color:#b98229;">Selling in Hawthorne</a> sets out the suburb-level detail.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Morningside.</strong> Morningside delivers a wide spread of property types and price points, and has benefited from spillover demand from buyers priced out of Bulimba and Hawthorne. Streets close to the rail station and Wynnum Road continue to see strong transactional volume. See <a href="/insights/selling-in-morningside" style="color:#b98229;">selling in Morningside</a> for context.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Cannon Hill.</strong> Cannon Hill has been one of the steadier performers at the more affordable end of the inner east, with proximity to the rail line and the retail precinct supporting both first home buyer and family demand. <a href="/insights/selling-in-cannon-hill" style="color:#b98229;">Selling in Cannon Hill</a> covers the local detail.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Murarrie.</strong> Murarrie has been a clear beneficiary of buyer migration looking for an inner east postcode at a price point below Cannon Hill, with the Hemmant ferry, the rail station, and proximity to Bulimba's amenities all supporting interest. <a href="/insights/selling-in-murarrie" style="color:#b98229;">Selling in Murarrie</a> goes into more depth.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Seven Hills.</strong> Seven Hills carries one of the smaller listing pools in the inner east and a strong pocket of character homes, particularly along the higher streets. Demand from buyers who want a quieter, leafier feel without leaving the inner east has remained consistent. See <a href="/insights/selling-in-seven-hills" style="color:#b98229;">selling in Seven Hills</a> for the campaign detail.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Norman Park.</strong> Norman Park has been one of the strongest performers within the inner east on a buyer-depth basis, particularly for properties in the Norman Park State School catchment. The streets running off Wynnum Road towards the river continue to trade above suburb median. <a href="/insights/selling-in-norman-park" style="color:#b98229;">Selling in Norman Park</a> sets out what to expect.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Camp Hill.</strong> Camp Hill remains a deep family home market with consistent demand for renovated post-war houses and well-presented Queenslanders, supported by the Coorparoo State School and Whites Hill catchment options. <a href="/insights/selling-in-camp-hill" style="color:#b98229;">Selling in Camp Hill</a> covers the suburb in more detail.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Carina.</strong> Carina has had a more varied performance through Q1 2026, with the higher-elevation, leafier streets trading well, while the parts of the suburb closer to busy roads have seen the longer days on market typical of more rate-sensitive segments. <a href="/insights/selling-in-carina" style="color:#b98229;">Selling in Carina</a> goes into the suburb-specific detail.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Coorparoo.</strong> Coorparoo blends a deep family home market in the established streets with a more variable apartment and townhouse market in the new-build pockets. School catchment properties remain in strong demand. <a href="/insights/selling-in-coorparoo" style="color:#b98229;">Selling in Coorparoo</a> sets out the campaign detail.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Infrastructure context</h2>

      <p>The medium-term infrastructure backdrop has continued to firm through 2026. The Queensland Government's 2032 Delivery Plan, released in March 2025, set out a $7.1 billion venue capital works program with the federal contribution refined under a renewed agreement. Earthworks at Victoria Park for the new Brisbane Stadium are scheduled to start in mid 2026, with construction following in early 2027. Cross River Rail, originally targeted for 2026 services, is now expected to open in 2029 after delays through construction and certification, which leaves the Boggo Road, Woolloongabba, Albert Street, and Roma Street precinct uplift on a longer timeline than initially modelled. None of this changes the fundamentals for an inner east family home selling in spring 2026, but it remains the medium-term context for buyers thinking about position relative to upgraded transport corridors.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Closing</h2>

      <p>The institutional data heading into spring 2026 supports a confident, well-prepared campaign for the right property in the inner east. Buyer depth is real, stock is tight, and the structural drivers of Brisbane demand remain intact. The cyclical pressures of higher rates and a more selective buyer make preparation, pricing, and method-selection more important than they have been in recent years, but they do not change the underlying case for a spring listing if the property and the timing genuinely line up.</p>

